Your manager is asking a very advanced Zero Trust question. He's essentially asking:

> "If I fully compromise the Digital Agent process itself, how do you stop me from pretending to be the Digital Agent?"



This is not solved by RFC 8693 or SPIFFE alone.


---

Scenario

Assume:

Attacker
      │
Gets RCE on Digital Agent
      │
Can execute arbitrary code
      │
Can access process memory

Now the attacker has:

Running process

Short-lived token

SPIFFE certificate (while valid)

Private key in memory (depending on implementation)


Now he asks:

> "Can't I call every other agent?"



This is called workload impersonation after compromise.


---

SPIFFE alone is NOT enough

SPIFFE proves

> "This workload was trusted when the certificate was issued."



It doesn't prove

> "This workload hasn't been compromised afterwards."



This is the key distinction.


---

