---

If your manager asks:

> "What if I spoof the Digital Agent?"



A good answer is:

> "Spoofing the Digital Agent is difficult because other agents authenticate it using SPIFFE-issued certificates over mTLS. Simply claiming to be the Digital Agent isn't enough—you need the corresponding private key."



Then acknowledge the next level:

> "However, if the Digital Agent itself is fully compromised and the attacker can use its live credentials, SPIFFE alone is insufficient. That's why enterprise systems combine SPIFFE with runtime security, remote attestation, micro-segmentation, continuous authorization, and rapid certificate rotation or revocation to minimize the blast radius and prevent lateral movement."




---

This is the answer that usually impresses security architects

> "SPIFFE protects against impersonation before compromise. Runtime security, remote attestation, service mesh authorization, and continuous identity validation protect against impersonation after compromise."



That demonstrates you understand the difference between identity and runtime trust, which is exactly the distinction your manager was probing.
